Here is a backend implementation to automate data collection jobs to run each morning using Node.js:

```javascript
// data-collector.js

const cron = require('node-cron');
const axios = require('axios');
const fs = require('fs').promises;
const path = require('path');

class DataCollector {
  constructor() {
    this.sources = [
      { 
        name: 'weather_api',
        url: 'https://api.weather.gov/stations/KNYC/observations' 
      },
      {
        name: 'stock_prices',
        url: 'https://api.polygon.io/v2/aggs/ticker/AAPL/range/1/day/2023-01-09/2023-01-09'
      }
    ];
  }

  async collectData(source) {
    try {
      const response = await axios.get(source.url);
      const filename = `${source.name}_${new Date().toISOString().slice(0,10)}.json`;
      const filepath = path.join(__dirname, 'data', filename);

      await fs.writeFile(filepath, JSON.stringify(response.data, null, 2));
      console.log(`Data saved to ${filepath}`);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(`Error collecting data from ${source.name}:`, error);
    }
  }

  scheduleJobs() {
    // Run every day at 7am
    cron.schedule('0 7 * * *', async () => {
      console.log('Running data collection jobs...');
      await Promise.all(this.sources.map(source => this.collectData(source)));
      console.log('Data collection complete');
    });
  }
}

module.exports = DataCollector;
```

```javascript
// index.js

const DataCollector = require('./data-collector');

const collector = new DataCollector();
collector.scheduleJobs();
```

This implements a `DataCollector` class that:

1. Defines an array of `sources` to collect data from, each with a name and URL. 
2. Has a `collectData` method to fetch data from a given source and save the response to a dated JSON file.
3. Uses the `node-cron` library to schedule the `collectData` job to run daily at 7am in the `scheduleJobs` method.

The `index.js` file simply creates an instance of `DataCollector` and calls `scheduleJobs` to start the cron job.

To run it:
1. Install dependencies:
```
npm install axios node-cron
```
2. Create a `data` directory for the output files
3. Run with `node index.js`

The data collection will run each morning at 7am and save the results to timestamped JSON files in the `data` directory.

This demonstrates a simple automated data collection system using Node.js. The same concepts of scheduling, fetching data from APIs, and persisting results can be implemented in any backend language/framework as needed.
